  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A local price trough where a low is flanked by higher lows on both sides, forming a three-candle pattern. It marks sell-side liquidity (sell stops) below. Swing lows serve as structural reference points for stop raids, liquidity sweeps, Fibonacci anchoring, and range definition. In bullish contexts, a sweep and subsequent close above the down-close candles that formed the low validates it as a protected swing, confirming a change in state of delivery.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Locate a candle whose low is lower than both the preceding and following candles, forming a trough (three-candle pattern), on any timeframe.",
    "Confirm that the low of the left candle is higher than the middle candle's low.",
    "Confirm that the low of the right candle is higher than the middle candle's low.",
    "Confirm that the high of the left candle is higher than the middle candle's high.",
    "Confirm that the high of the right candle is higher than the middle candle's high.",
    "Confirm the pattern is complete when the third candle closes.",
    "Confirm that the low has resting sell-side liquidity below it, often indicated by a prior consolidation low or higher-timeframe candle low.",
    "A sweep (stop raid) occurs when price trades below the low and then reverses; confirmation often requires a candle closure back inside the prior range (candle 2 closure) or a close above the body of the sweeping candle (candle 3 closure).",
    "Validate the swing low as a protected structural pivot by waiting for a close above the series of down-close candles that formed it (change in state of delivery); if the move is messy, treat the entire down move and wait for a close above its origin.",
    "The low must reach into a point of interest (e.g., fair value gap, order block, equal lows) to be considered tradable; reject lows that form without such confluence.",
    "On retracements, a valid swing low forms on a slow, shallow move; aggressive displacement back into the range signifies a reversal rather than a swing low.",
    "For range-based trading, pair the swing low with the corresponding swing high to define a range; anchor Fibonacci tools from swing high to low to mark equilibrium, discount, and premium zones.",
    "In an uptrend, subsequent swing lows should be higher than the previous (higher low); in a downtrend, subsequent swing lows should be lower than the previous (lower low).",
    "Mark the low as the lower boundary of the price range, with the corresponding swing high forming the complete analysis range; also use as the endpoint anchor (fib 0) for Fibonacci retracement tools."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Swing lows represent sell-side liquidity that price often sweeps before reversing higher. A sweep of a prior swing low, followed by a close above the down-close candles that formed it (change in state of delivery), validates the low as a protected structural pivot, allowing long entries with stops below the swing low, targeting overhead liquidity. Swing lows serve as the lower anchor for Fibonacci tools to identify discount, premium, and OTE zones. Unswept swing lows below act as draw-on-liquidity targets for bearish moves. In uptrends, each new protected swing low confirms continuation. Also used with swing highs to define ranges and detect market structure shifts (CHoCH/BOS).",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Treating a low as a protected swing before a close above the series of down-close candles (change in state of delivery) has occurred.",
    "Anticipating a reversal or taking long entries without waiting for the swing low to be swept (stop raid).",
    "Treating an unconfirmed low (failure swing) as support when no change in state of delivery has occurred, expecting it to hold rather than being taken out.",
    "Marking random swing lows without requiring a point of interest (fair value gap, order block, equal lows, etc.) for the low to be valid.",
    "Accepting a sweep that only marginally pierces the low without a full-bodied displacement candle as a valid sweep.",
    "Treating a sweep that consolidates (rather than producing a V-shape reversal or a decisive close back inside) as a valid reversal.",
    "Failing to update the equilibrium range or Fibonacci anchors as new swing lows form, leading to outdated premium/discount zones.",
    "Placing stop loss on the order block low instead of the swing low, risking premature stop-out from wicks.",
    "Assuming a protected low will hold after expansion is met with opposing expansion, instead of recognizing it as a reversal signature.",
    "Focusing on minor internal lows while ignoring the most obvious external swing lows of a range.",
    "Not confirming a low with a required candle 2 or candle 3 closure, relying only on visual appearance of a low.",
    "Treating every swing low as a reversal point rather than recognizing that stacked higher lows can act as low-resistance liquidity that price runs through.",
    "Right candle not fully confirmed before labeling the swing low, leading to structural misjudgment.",
    "Price only touches the swing low but closing position not yet confirmed, prematurely judging reversal direction, ignoring the key verification step of close price breakthrough.",
    "Only looking at lower timeframe swing low break to judge trend reversal, ignoring higher timeframe overall trend direction (higher timeframe may just be retracement).",
    "Confusing nested secondary swing lows within a range with the main swing low, causing confusion with multiple overlapping ranges.",
    "Using only a single fixed range, ignoring new swing lows continuously generated during price movement, causing failure to dynamically update the range.",
    "Mistaking temporary lows swept within a range as valid swing lows, when these lows may just be liquidity being swept.",
    "In bullish scenarios, completing Fibonacci range labeling before the swing high is confirmed."
  ],
